TITLE: Even with slower inflation, consumer sentiment weakened sharply in November, survey shows
SUMMARY: The University of Michigan Survey of Consumers posted a 54.7 reading for November, down 8.7% from the previous month's reading.

TITLE: UK on the brink of recession after economy contracts by 0.2% in the third quarter
SUMMARY: The third-quarter contraction was less than the -0.5% expected by analysts.

TITLE: Fed officials welcome inflation news but still see tighter policy ahead
SUMMARY: Federal Reserve officials welcomed Thursday's inflation news but cautioned against getting too excited by the data.

TITLE: Consumer prices rose 0.4% in October, less than expected, as inflation eases
SUMMARY: The consumer price index was expected to rise 0.6% from September to October and 7.9% from a year ago, according to Dow Jones estimates.

TITLE: Consumer confidence is near its lowest in a decade, and that could be a problem for Biden
SUMMARY: Anxiety over the cost of living and the direction of the economy could prove costly to President Biden — and his fellow Democrats.

TITLE: The unemployment rate for Black men fell in October, but so did labor force participation
SUMMARY: Workers of color continue to see higher rates of unemployment than their white counterparts.

TITLE: Here's where the jobs are for October 2022 — in one chart
SUMMARY: The health-care and manufacturing sectors added notable gains.

TITLE: U.S. payrolls surged by 261,000 in October, better than expected as hiring remains strong
SUMMARY: Nonfarm payrolls were expected to increase by 205,000 in October, according to Dow Jones estimates.

TITLE: Labor costs show slower rise, while trade deficit widens and jobless claims nudge lower
SUMMARY: The cost of labor rose less than expected, but low productivity helped keep pressure on inflation in the third quarter.

TITLE: Private payrolls rose 239,000 in October, better than expected, while wages increased 7.7%, ADP says
SUMMARY: Companies added 239,000 positions in October, ahead of the Dow Jones estimate of 195,000, ADP reported Wednesday.

TITLE: Job openings surged in September despite Fed efforts to cool labor market
SUMMARY: Employment openings for the month totaled 10.72 million, well above the FactSet estimate of 9.85 million.

TITLE: Key inflation gauge for the Fed rose 0.5% in September, in line with expectations
SUMMARY: The core personal consumption expenditures price index increased 0.5% from the previous month and accelerated 5.1% over the past 12 months.

TITLE: U.S. consumer spending seeing a 'mitigation' in growth not a slowdown, says Bank of America CEO
SUMMARY: Consumers and corporations have strong underlying credit and are not holding back, Brian Moynihan said.

TITLE: U.S. GDP accelerated at 2.6% pace in Q3, better than expected as growth turns positive
SUMMARY: Gross domestic product was expected to grow at a 2.3% annualized pace in the third quarter, according to Dow Jones.

TITLE: Powell again is facing political pressure as worries mount over the economy
SUMMARY: No stranger to political pressure, the Fed chief this week found himself the focus of concern in a letter from Democratic Sen. Sherrod Brown.

TITLE: Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan CEOs tip U.S. economy for recession as labor tightness keeps Fed aggressive
SUMMARY: Goldman Sachs CEO David Solomon and JPMorgan CEO Jamie Dimon both expect a U.S. recession.

TITLE: Inflation is dominating the conversation on earnings calls. Here's what execs are saying
SUMMARY: One thing is clear at the start of the corporate earnings season: Inflation remains a hot topic for company executives.

TITLE: U.S. budget deficit cut in half for biggest decrease ever amid Covid spending declines
SUMMARY: The U.S. budget deficit was sliced in half for fiscal 2022, the biggest drop in history following two years of huge Covid-related spending.

TITLE: Elon Musk says a global recession could last until the spring of 2024
SUMMARY: Tesla founder Elon Musk thinks the global economic contraction can last for another year and a half.

TITLE: Here’s how venture capital is helping to lift the next generation of Latinos in finance
SUMMARY: Latinos are underrepresented in all areas of finance. Groups of venture capital firms are looking to change that.

TITLE: An often-overlooked economic measure is signaling serious trouble ahead
SUMMARY: According to The Conference Board's Leading Economic Indicators index, conditions worsened in September.

TITLE: Multigenerational Hispanic households are under pressure as rates surge and homes remain costly
SUMMARY: Rising interest rates and pricier homes have increased the pressure on multigenerational households seeking adequate housing.

TITLE: Jeff Bezos is the latest to warn on the economy, saying it's time to 'batten down the hatches'
SUMMARY: Amazon founder Jeff Bezos has become the latest corporate leader to warn about the state of the economy.

TITLE: After two years of shipping snarls, things are starting to turn around
SUMMARY: Port congestions and container shortages are easing as Chinese exports slow in the face of waning demand from Western economies, logistics data shows.

TITLE: Consumer spending was flat in September and below expectations as inflation takes toll
SUMMARY: Retail and food services sales in total were little changed for the month after rising 0.4% in August.

TITLE: Inflation increased 0.4% in September, more than expected despite rate hikes
SUMMARY: The consumer price index was expected to increase 0.3% in September, according to Dow Jones estimates.

TITLE: Wholesale prices rose 0.4% in September, more than expected as inflation persists
SUMMARY: The producer price index was expected to rise 0.2% in September, according to Dow Jones estimates.

TITLE: Inflation expectations ease, while spending outlook tumbles, Fed consumer survey shows
SUMMARY: Consumers expect the inflation rate a year from now to be 5.4%, the lowest number in a year and a decline from 5.75% in August.

TITLE: U.S. should pump more oil to avert war-level energy crisis, says JPMorgan's Jamie Dimon
SUMMARY: JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon said Monday that the U.S. should forge ahead in pumping more oil and gas to help alleviate the global energy crisis.

TITLE: Ark's Cathie Wood issues open letter to the Fed, saying it is risking an economic 'bust'
SUMMARY: The Fed likely is making a mistake in its hardline stance against inflation, Ark Invest's Cathie Wood said Monday.
